review_blob: Highly Carbonated which I enjoyed.  Poured with little, dark tan head.  I could smell the raspberry but the only time the flavor of raspberry was prominent was when I let it chill for too long and it was too cold. Other than that there was a dark malt and chocolate flavor. Overall a fun beer to drink.
Overall an average ale but there was a smokey flavor about it that sets it apart from other average ales. No head or aroma to it at all.  Goes well with garlic and hot sauce
In a bottle at Stubbs BBQ.  Went really well with my brisket.  Nice amount of hops and very drinkable.
beer_name: Real Ale Rio Blanco Pale Ale

review_blob: On tap at the Jackalope in Austin, TX.  Not bad for a lighter, refreshing ale on a hot afternoon in Texas. I didnt detect a huge amount of hops but a sweet fruit maybe a melon or peach?
I enjoyed this beer very much.  It was a good balance of malt and hops.  I felt as if the flavor had a slight blueberry/cranberry hint to it with a light caramel/vanilla finish.

I was very sad to see Dogwood close and it was because of this beer.  I first tried it as a sample at the Rusty Nail on Buford Highway and immediately went to Greens and bought a 6-pack.  While not the greatest beer in the world, it was intriguing enough for me to see if Dogwood could bottle a consistent beer.  This was the only beer made by Dogwood that I ever had that didnt have a skunky bottle in the pack.
the only thing I can say about this was that I felt like I was drinking a hot chocolate after it cooled off, which isnt necessarily a bad thing.

I had been told many a great thing about fat tire and must say that it is in the running for the worst tasting beer I have tried.  I am usually open to trying new things but I had to choke this one down.  The taste is similar to that of the name a fat tire, one thats been sitting on the side of the road after being blowm out from under a semi after it hit a skunk.
I had this one on tap during SXSW in 2004 and must say that it was a welcome change to my week of some pretty terrible beers.  I am looking forward to this one again this year
beer_name: Copper Tank Lost My Mind Barleywine

review_blob: Pours with a nice tan head.  Very subtle chocolate flavor.  Definitely hoppy as far as stouts go.  Alot more carbonation than wanted but should expect from a Sierra Nevada brew.  Overall, it will work for a stout on a regular basis.

When I first tried this beer I guess I was expecting something almost sour tasting, like a Granny Smith apple but was pleased by a very relaxed and clean taste, with an almost oily finish as if it were a fine olive oil.
A great example of an IPA.  I had been hearing about this one for a while and was glad to finally find it.

Dark beer and whiskey combine to create one of the greatest beers ever.  I was recommended this one at the Brickstore Pub in Decatur, GA after they had run out of the Dogwood Winter Ale that had be aged in Jack Daniels casks.  I enjoy the rich coffee, whiskey and chocolate flavors and smooth finish of this beer.
beer_name: Harviestoun Old Engine Oil Special Reserve

review_blob: Refreshing and light.  Great nose.  Pours similar to a light lager in my opinion.  A great beer for a lazy Atlanta summer afternoon
While living in Atlanta I consumed Sweetwater brews often and always go back for the 420
